\bigskip


\hrule
\setlength{\columnsep}{1em}
\begin{multicols}{3}
  \setlength\parfillskip{0pt}
\itshape
This is a basic summary reference sheet for the grammar Syrian Arabic. For a more detailed grammatical description, please refer \textit{A~Reference Grammar of Syrian Arabic} (Cowell, Georgetown University Press, 2005), to which page references are provided in the margin. The transcription system is based on \textit{Alif Baa} (Brustad et~al., Georgetown University Press, 2010) and extended with the vowels \textit{e/ee} and~\textit{o/oo}. The Arabic writing represent written Syrian Arabic, as used in text messaging, advertisement, etc. There is some variation in this form of writing, especially in the degree to which Standard Arabic orthography is retained.
\end{multicols}

\setlength{\columnsep}{20pt}

\section{Phonematics}

\subsection{Consonants}


\begin{multicols}{2}

  \begin{tabularx}{\linewidth}{X>{\itshape}c>{\itshape}cX>{\itshape}c>{\itshape}cX}

&ʾ    & \textarabic{ا}&& D   & \textarabic{ض}   &    \\
&b    & \textarabic{ب}&& T    & \textarabic{ط}  &     \\
&t    & \textarabic{ت}&& (DH) & \textarabic{ظ}  &     \\
&(th) & \textarabic{ث}&& ʿ    & \textarabic{ع}  &     \\
&j    & \textarabic{ج}&& gh   & \textarabic{غ}  &     \\
&H    & \textarabic{ح}&& f    & \textarabic{ف}  &     \\
&kh   & \textarabic{خ}&& (q)  & \textarabic{ق}  &     \\
&d    & \textarabic{د}&& k    & \textarabic{ك}  &     \\
&(dh) & \textarabic{ذ}&& l    & \textarabic{ل}  &     \\
&r    & \textarabic{ر}&& m    & \textarabic{م}  &     \\
&z    & \textarabic{ز}&& n    & \textarabic{ن}  &     \\
&s    & \textarabic{س}&& h    & \textarabic{ه}  &     \\
&sh   & \textarabic{ش}&& w    & \textarabic{و}  &     \\
&S    & \textarabic{ص}&& y    & \textarabic{ي}  &    \\
                 
\end{tabularx}

Phonemes within parenthesis are specific to Standard Arabic and are not part of the Syrian Arabic phonemic system, but they may appear in words perceived as formal, literary, or technical (\textit{al-qurʾaan, dimuqraatiyya}). For details on the Arabic writing system, see \textit{The~Arabic Writing System}.\footnote{\url{http://andreasmhallberg.github.io/documents/arabic-letters-and-vowel-markers.tex.pdf}} 

\end{multicols}

\subsection{Vowels}
\needspace{5cm}


\begin{multicols}{2}

  \begin{tabularx}{\linewidth}{X>{\itshape}l>{\itshape}lcX}

    & \upshape Short & \multicolumn{2}{l}{Long} & \\
    & i              & ii                       & \textarabic{ي} & \\
    & u              & uu                       & \textarabic{و} & \\
    & a              & aa                       & \textarabic{ا} & \\
    & e              & ee                       & \textarabic{ي} & \\
    & o              & oo                       & \textarabic{و} & \\

  \end{tabularx}

Only long vowels have an orthographic representation. Vowel diacritics are generally not used in written Arabic vernacular.

\end{multicols}

\subsection{Standard to Syrian phonemic conversion rules}\label{subsec:converston}

\begin{multicols}{2}

  \begin{tabularx}{\linewidth}{>{\itshape}l@{~→~}>{\itshape}lX>{\itshape}l@{~→~}>{\itshape}lr}

  ay                     & ee        &  & bayt     & beet    & \textarabic{بيت}\\
  aw                     & oo        &  & yawm     & yoom    & \textarabic{يوم}\\
  q                      & ʾ         &  & daqiiqa  & daʾiiʾa & \textarabic{دقيقة}\\
  th                     & t         &  & thalatha & tlaate  & \textarabic{تلاتة}\\
    \multicolumn{1}{c}{} & \llap{(}s &  & mathalan & masalan\rlap{)} & \textarabic{مثلا}\\
  dh                     & d         &  & dhahab   & dahab\rlap{)}   & \textarabic{دهب}\\
    \multicolumn{1}{c}{} & \llap{(}z &  & idha     & iza     & \textarabic{اذا}\\
  DH                     & D         &  & DHuhr    & Duhr    & \textarabic{ضهر}\\

\end{tabularx}

\columnbreak

These conversion rules represent regular sound relations in Standard--Syrian cognates. Written Syrian Arabic often reflect Standard Arabic orthography. Standard Arabic pronunciation is often retained in formal or literary words (\textit{dimuqraaTiyye}) and in non-Syrian Arabic place names (\textit{al-qaahira} `Cairo'). Standard Arabic \textit{th} and~\textit{dh} are in these context rendered \textit{s} and~\textit{z} respectively.

\end{multicols}


\section{Pronouns}

\subsection{Personal pronouns}

\begin{multicols}{2}

\begin{tabular}{>{\itshape}l>{\itshape}l>{\itshape}lrrr
  }
  \toprule
  \upshape{Indep.} 
  & \multicolumn{2}{l}{Attached}
  &  \multicolumn{2}{r}{\textarabic{متصل}}
  & \textarabic{منفصل}\\
  \midrule

  ana    & -i   & (-ya)  &                    & \textarabic{ـي}                      & \textarabic{انا}    \\
  inti   & -ak  & (-k)   &                    & \textarabic{ـك}                      & \textarabic{انت}    \\
  inta   & -ik  & (-ki)  & \textarabic{(ـكي)} & \textarabic{ـك}                      & \textarabic{انتي}   \\
  huwwe  & -u   & (-h)   & \textarabic{(ـه)}  & \textarabic{ـو\rlap{/\,ـه}}          & \textarabic{هو}     \\
  hiyye  & -a   & (-ha)  &                    & \textarabic{ـها}\rlap{\footnotemark} & \textarabic{هي}     \\
  niHna  & -na  &        &                    & \textarabic{ـنا}                     & \textarabic{نحنا}   \\
  intu   & -kon &        &                    & \textarabic{ـكن}                     & \textarabic{انتو}  \\
  hunnen & -on  & (-hun) & \textarabic{(ـهن)} & \textarabic{ـن}                      & \textarabic{هنن}    \\

\bottomrule

\end{tabular}
\footnotetext{The~\textarabic{ه} in~\textarabic{ـها} is only pronounced if used with a word ending in a vowel.}

\columnbreak

\noindent
The forms in parenthesis are used on words with final vowel: \textit{aʿTaa-ki} `he~gave~you'. Attached pronouns are used for

\begin{tabular}{lll}
   
  prep. compl. & \textit{maʿ-u} &`with-him'\\
   possession& \textit{ktaab-u} &`his book'\\
   direct object& \textit{katabt-u} &`I wrote it'\\
   indirect object& \textit{katabt-l-u} &`I~wrote~for~him'\footnotemark\\
\end{tabular}

The\page{480f} connective~\textit{-l-} for indirect objects may take the form \textit{-el-} to prevent consonant clusters: \textit{katabt‑el‑kun} `I~worte for you~(pl.)'.

\footnotetext{A direct object may then be added with the word \textit{yaa-:} \textit{katabt-l-ak yaa-h} `I~wrote it for you'.}

\end{multicols}

\subsection{Demonstrative pronouns} \page{552}

\begin{tabular}{l>{\itshape}l>{\itshape}lrr}
\toprule

                   & \upshape Proximal & \upshape Distant & \textarabic{بعيد}   & \textarabic{قريب} \\
  \midrule
  Masc.            & haada             & hadaak           & \textarabic{هداك}   & \textarabic{هاد}\\
  Fem.             & haay              & hadiik           & \textarabic{هديك}   & \textarabic{هاي} \\
  Pl.              & hadool            & haadooliik       & \textarabic{هدوليك} & \textarabic{هدول} \\

  \bottomrule
\end{tabular}


\section{Prepositions}\page{176ff}

\begin{multicols}{2}

\begin{tabular}{>{\itshape}lrl}

   \ayntab ʿand              & \textarabic{عند} & with, at\\
   \ayntab ʿa-               & \textarabic{عـ}  & to\\
   \ayntab ʿala\footnotemark & \textarabic{على} & on\\
   men                       & \textarabic{من}  & from\\
   Hadd                      & \textarabic{حد}  & next to\\
   fooʾ                      & \textarabic{فوق} & above\\
   taHt                      & \textarabic{تحت} & below\\
   maʿ                       & \textarabic{مع}  & with\\
   wara                      & \textarabic{ورا} & behind\\
   ʾuddaam                   & \textarabic{قدام} & in front of\\

\end{tabular}

\footnotetext{\textit{ʿala} becomes \textit{ʿalee-} \textarabic{عليـ} when used with a pronominal suffix: \textit{ʿalee-ha} `on~it/her'.}

\columnbreak

\begin{tabular}{>{\itshape}l>{\itshape}lrl}
  w. noun&\multicolumn{2}{l}{w. pronoun}\\
  \addlinespace

   bi-  & fii-     & \textarabic{بـ/فيـ}     & in, at\\
   la-  & el-      & \textarabic{لـ/الـ}     & for (ownership)\\
   been & beenaat- & \textarabic{بين/بيناتـ} & between, among\\

\end{tabular}

  The three pronouns above have two forms for use with nouns and pronouns respectively:

  \begin{tabular}{lrl}
    \textit{bi-l-bayt}&\textarabic{بالبيت}&`in the house'\\
    \textit{fii-h}&\textarabic{فيه}&`in~it'\\
  \end{tabular}

\end{multicols}

\section{Question words}

\begin{multicols}{2}

\begin{tabular}{>{\itshape}lrl}

    shuu?  & \textarabic{شو؟}    & what?  \\
    miin?  & \textarabic{مين؟}   & who?   \\
    eemta? & \textarabic{ايمتى؟} & when?   \\
    kiif?  & \textarabic{كيف؟}   & how?    \\
    ween?  & \textarabic{وين؟}    & where?  \\
    leesh?  & \textarabic{ليش؟}    & why?  \\

\end{tabular}
  
  Yes/no question formed with rising intonation, or with an elongated clause-final syllable.\page{379} \textit{Ween} and \textit{kiif} take attached pronouns:

  \begin{tabular}{lrl}
    \textit{ween-ak?}  & \textarabic{وينك؟} & `where are you?'\\
    \textit{kiif-ak?}  & \textarabic{كيفك؟} & `how are you?' \\
  \end{tabular}


\end{multicols}

\section{Verbs}

\subsection{Inflection}

\begin{multicols}{2}

  \begin{tabularx}{\linewidth}{X@{}>{
  \itshape}r@{{\itshape-ktib}}>{\itshape}l
  >{\itshape katab}l
  rr
  }

  \toprule
    & \multicolumn{2}{l}{Non-past}&\multicolumn{1}{l}{Past} & \llap{\textarabic{المضارع}}&\textarabic{الماضي}\\
  \midrule

  I          & i  &    & -t    & \textarabic{اكتب}  & \textarabic{كتبت}   \\
  you~(ms.) & ti &    & -t     & \textarabic{تكتب}  & \textarabic{كتبت}   \\
  you~(fs.)  & ti & -i & -ti   & \textarabic{تكتبي} & \textarabic{كتبتي}  \\
  he         & yi &    &       & \textarabic{يكتب}  & \textarabic{كتب}     \\
  she        & ti &    & -it   & \textarabic{تكتب}  & \textarabic{كتبت}   \\
  we         & ni &    & -na   & \textarabic{نكتب}  & \textarabic{كتبنا}  \\
  you~(pl.)  & ti & -u & -tu   & \textarabic{تكتبو} & \textarabic{كتبتو}  \\
  they       & yi & -u & -u    & \textarabic{يكتبو} & \textarabic{كتبو}   \\

  \bottomrule
\end{tabularx}

\bigskip


The pronoun is often omitted. The non-past verb is always preceded by one of the following:

  \begin{tabular}{lrl}

  \textit{b-}\footnotemark         & \textarabic{بـ}   &habitual, generalities\\
    \ayntab\textit{ʿam} &\textarabic{عم}    &progressive\page{320}\\
  \textit{Ha-/raH}    &\textarabic{حـ/رح} &future\\

\end{tabular}
  \footnotetext{For 1pl. the \textit{b-} prefix is partially assimilated and pronounced as \textit{m:} \mbox{\textit{mniktib}}. This is often reflected in Arabic orthography: \textarabic{منكتب}.}

  or an auxiliary verb, in which case both the auxiliary and the main verb are inflected for person:

  \begin{tabular}{lrl}

      \textit{biddu yiktib}    & \textarabic{بدو يكتب} & `he wants to write'\\
      \textit{byiHibb yiktib}  & \textarabic{بيحب يكتب}& `he likes to write' \\
      \textit{kaan yiktib}     & \textarabic{كان يكتب}& `he was writing'   \\

  \end{tabular}

\end{multicols}

\subsection{\textit{Kaan}} 
\begin{multicols}{2}

  \begin{tabular}{l@{}>{
  \itshape}l>{\itshape}l
@{\hskip 0pt plus 100 pt}rr
  }
  \toprule
  & \multicolumn{1}{l}{Non-past}&\multicolumn{1}{l}{Past} & \textarabic{المضارع} & \textarabic{الماضي} \\
  \midrule

  I         & ikuun   & kent     & \textarabic{اكون}  & \textarabic{كنت}  \\
  you (ms.) & tikuun  & kent     & \textarabic{تكون}  & \textarabic{كنت}  \\
  you (fs.) & tikuuni & kenti    & \textarabic{تكوني} & \textarabic{كنتي} \\
  he        & yikuun  & kaan     & \textarabic{يكون}  & \textarabic{كان}  \\
  she       & tikuun  & kaanit   & \textarabic{تكون}  & \textarabic{كانت} \\
  we        & nikuun  & kenna    & \textarabic{نكون}  & \textarabic{كنا}  \\
  you (pl.) & tikuunu & kentu    & \textarabic{تكونو} & \textarabic{كنتو} \\
  they      & yikuunu & kaanu    & \textarabic{يكونو} & \textarabic{كانو} \\

  \bottomrule
\end{tabular}

\textit{Kaan} is used to place equational (verb-less) clauses in past tense: \textit{kaan aHmad Taaleb}, or with verbs to express a past ongoing event: \textit{aHmad kaan (ʿam) yiktib}.

\end{multicols}

\subsection{Pseudo-verbs}

\textit{bidd‑}~`want' and \textit{ʿind‑}~'has' are inflected for person with attached pronouns like nouns, \textit{bidd‑u} `he~wants'; \textit{ʿind-u} `he~has', but take the verbal negation \textit{maa} and direct objects. They are inflected for past with the auxiliary verb \textit{kaan}.


\section{Negation}

\begin{tabular}{lrl}

  \textit{maa}   & \textarabic{ما} & verbs \\
  \textit{muu}  & \textarabic{مو} & non verbal clauses \\
  \textit{laʾʾa} & \textarabic{لأ}  & answering in the negative \\

\end{tabular}


\pagebreak
\section{Numerals} \page{170f}

\newcommand{\onetwoinfo}{The numerals \textit{one} and \textit{two} are used only for emphasis or contrast, or when ordering in restaurants (\textit{itneen shaay} `two tee'). Otherwise, the lone noun in singular or dual is used.}
\newcommand{\threeteninfo}{The \textit{absolute} form of the numeral is used when it not followed by a noun, hand the \textit{construct} form when it followed by a noun: \textit{tlatt awlaad} `three boys.' Numerals 3--10 have a special construct form with a final~\textit{-t} when used with one of three nouns \textit{ayyaam} 'days', \textit{shuhuur} 'months', and \textit{aalaaf} 'thousands': \textit{khamst~ayyam} 'five~days'.} 
\newcommand{\teensinfo}{Numerals 11---19 are constructed of the unit number and the ending \textit{‑taʿsh}, with som irregularites in 11, 12, and 15. On the construct form the suffix~\textit{-ar} is added.} 
\newcommand{\cententialinfo}{Cententials are constructed of the construct form of the unit and the ending \textit{‑iin}, with only 20 having an irregular form. In complex numbers, the unit number appear before the centential in its absolute form. The unite and the centential are connected with the conjuction~\textit{u-}: \textit{sabʿa u‑tlaatin}, `thirty‑six'.} 

\begin{tabularx}{\textwidth}{l
  >{\itshape}l>{\itshape}l
  rrrX
  }

  \cmidrule{1-5}
  & \upshape Absolute  & \upshape Construct & \textarabic{مضاف}& \llap{\textarabic{غير مضاف}}\\
  \cmidrule{1-5}

